## Architecture — Supabase API-Only Backend

There is no Node.js server. No API routes in the frontend. No Server Actions. No middleware.ts.

- **Frontend:** React SPA communicates directly with Supabase via `@supabase/supabase-js` (publishable key + JWT)
- **Authorization:** RLS on every table — the JWT scopes all queries to the current user. RLS is the single authorization boundary.
- **Server-side logic:** Supabase Edge Functions only — for webhooks, cron, transactional email, service_role operations, and any logic that must not run in the browser.

## Supabase Client

- One client in `src/lib/supabase.ts` using `createClient()` with `VITE_SUPABASE_URL` and `VITE_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY`
- All frontend code (routes, components, hooks) uses this single client instance
- Never import `@supabase/supabase-js` directly in route or component files — always import the pre-initialized client from `src/lib/supabase`
- The client automatically attaches the user's JWT to every request — RLS handles authorization

```typescript
// src/lib/supabase.ts
import { createClient } from "@supabase/supabase-js";
import type { Database } from "@/lib/database.types";

const supabaseUrl = import.meta.env.VITE_SUPABASE_URL;
const supabaseKey = import.meta.env.VITE_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY;

if (!supabaseUrl || !supabaseKey) {
  throw new Error("Missing VITE_SUPABASE_URL or VITE_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY in .env.local");
}

export const supabase = createClient<Database>(supabaseUrl, supabaseKey);
```

## Auth

- Use Supabase Auth exclusively — no custom JWT, no custom session management
- Auth state managed by `AuthProvider` in `src/lib/auth.tsx` wrapping the app
- `useAuth()` hook provides: `user`, `session`, `loading`, `signIn()`, `signOut()`
- **AuthProvider must subscribe to `supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange()`** to handle token refresh, session expiry, and sign-out events. Redirect to `/login` on `SIGNED_OUT` event. Without this, expired tokens cause silent query failures.
- Auth guard is a React Router layout route at `src/routes/_app/layout.tsx` — checks session, redirects to `/login` if absent
- OAuth callback handled at `src/routes/_auth/callback/route.tsx`

```typescript
// src/routes/_app/layout.tsx — Auth guard pattern
import { Outlet, Navigate } from "react-router";
import { useAuth } from "@/lib/auth";

export default function AppLayout() {
  const { session, loading } = useAuth();
  if (loading) return <LoadingSkeleton />;
  if (!session) return <Navigate to="/login" replace />;
  return <Outlet />;
}
```

## Data Access

- Typed query functions in `src/lib/data/*.ts` — one file per domain entity (optional organizational layer)
- Routes and hooks call these functions or use Supabase client directly
- All entity interfaces live in `src/lib/api-types.ts` — single source of truth
- Generated types from `supabase gen types typescript` go to `src/lib/database.types.ts` — api-types.ts re-exports or extends these

## Database

- **RLS required on every table — no exceptions.** Never create a table without RLS policies.
- Common RLS pattern: `auth.uid() = user_id` for row-level ownership
- After every MCP `apply_migration` call, write the same SQL to a local file in `supabase/migrations/` named `YYYYMMDDHHmmss_short_description.sql` — remote and local must never drift
- Use `supabase gen types typescript --project-id <ref> > src/lib/database.types.ts` after schema changes
- Default to SQL for deterministic queries — no LLM for structured data
- Add indexes on columns used in WHERE clauses and JOIN conditions — especially `user_id` foreign keys

### RLS Policy Patterns

```sql
-- Standard ownership policy
ALTER TABLE goals ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

CREATE POLICY "Users read own goals"
  ON goals FOR SELECT
  USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

CREATE POLICY "Users insert own goals"
  ON goals FOR INSERT
  WITH CHECK (auth.uid() = user_id);

CREATE POLICY "Users update own goals"
  ON goals FOR UPDATE
  USING (auth.uid() = user_id)
  WITH CHECK (auth.uid() = user_id);

CREATE POLICY "Users delete own goals"
  ON goals FOR DELETE
  USING (auth.uid() = user_id);
```

## Edge Functions

All server-side logic lives in `supabase/functions/`. Each function is a Deno module with a single `index.ts`.

| Use case | Example | Why Edge Function |
|---|---|---|
| Payment webhooks | `supabase/functions/payment-webhook/` | Verify signatures, use service_role to update credits |
| Transactional email | `supabase/functions/send-email/` | Resend API key is server-only |
| Scheduled jobs | `supabase/functions/cron-*/` | Push notifications, cleanup, digests |
| Admin operations | `supabase/functions/admin-*/` | Service role operations outside user context |

### Edge Function Rules

- Verify webhook signatures before processing — use the provider's verification method
- Check idempotency before writes — skip duplicate event IDs
- Use `createClient()` with `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` from `Deno.env` — webhooks have no user session
- Edge Functions have a 2-second CPU limit and 150-second wall clock limit — keep them lean
- Never import frontend code into Edge Functions — they are separate Deno modules
- Deploy via `supabase functions deploy [name]` in the devops-agent deploy flow

```typescript
// supabase/functions/payment-webhook/index.ts — pattern
import { createClient } from "https://esm.sh/@supabase/supabase-js@2";

Deno.serve(async (req) => {
  // 1. Verify signature
  const signature = req.headers.get("x-webhook-signature");
  if (!verifySignature(signature, await req.text())) {
    return new Response("Invalid signature", { status: 401 });
  }

  // 2. Parse event
  const event = JSON.parse(await req.text());

  // 3. Idempotency check
  const supabase = createClient(
    Deno.env.get("SUPABASE_URL")!,
    Deno.env.get("SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY")!
  );

  const { data: existing } = await supabase
    .from("webhook_events")
    .select("id")
    .eq("event_id", event.id)
    .single();

  if (existing) return new Response("Already processed", { status: 200 });

  // 4. Process event + record
  // ...

  return new Response("OK", { status: 200 });
});
```

## Webhooks

- Verify signatures before processing
- Check idempotency before writes — skip duplicate event IDs
- Use service_role client — webhooks have no user session
- Return 200 quickly — defer heavy processing if needed
- Log webhook event ID + status for debugging

## Validation

- Use `zod` schemas for validating user input in Edge Functions
- Frontend forms validate with the same zod schemas (shared types in `src/lib/api-types.ts`)
- Never expose raw database errors to the client — transform to `{ error: { code, message } }`
